{
  "query": "Does the effectiveness of using fences to exclude livestock from shrublands vary between different countries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence varies by country: In the UK, multiple studies reported increases in shrub cover or abundance and increases in shrub biomass and heather plant biomass/height inside livestock exclosures; some UK studies also found mixed or no effects on shrub cover, and changes in other vegetation metrics (e.g., increased vegetation height/biomass, lower species richness, and both decreases and increases in grass cover) (1545). In Germany, fencing increased shrub biomass (1545). In Denmark, fenced areas had higher heather presence or cover (1545). In the USA, findings included decreased woody plant cover inside exclosures, mixed or no effects on shrub cover, no difference in forb cover, and both decreases and increases in grass cover; a deer-exclusion study found increased shrub height but not shrub cover (1545, 1662). In Finland, fencing did not alter grass cover and did not alter herb abundance (1545). Overall, reported effects differ across the UK, Germany, Denmark, the USA, and Finland (1545, 1662).",
